[[File:Remains of the former Hurst park racecourse, Graburn Way, East Molesey (8149160057).jpg|thumb|Brick piers at the entrance of the former Hurst Park racecourse, in 2012]]
'''Hurst Park Racecourse''' was a [[racecourse]] at [[Moulsey Hurst]], [[West Molesey]], [[Surrey]]. It was first laid out in 1890. The racecourse was the scene of an arson attack by [[Kitty Marion]] and Clara Elizabeth Giveen. The two suffragettes were establishing a revenge attack following the death of [[Emily Davison]] at the Derby in 1913.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp58990/clara-elizabeth-giveen|title=Clara Elizabeth Giveen - Person - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>

The [[Triumph Hurdle]] was run here from 1939 until the course closed. The last race to be held here was the Byfleet Stakes, the 4.30 on Wednesday 10 October 1962, was won by the 11/8 favourite Anassa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moleseyhistory.co.uk/books/molesey/tm/tm_19.htm|title=Thameside Molesey - Hurst Park|website=www.moleseyhistory.co.uk}}</ref> [[Mansfield Town F.C.]] bought one of the grandstands for later use as the West Stand at [[Field Mill]] and [[Ascot Racecourse]] purchased 20 acres of turf which was used to lay down Ascot's new [[National Hunt racing]] course.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dennis |first1=Steve |title=Desert Orchid thriller the highlight of 50 years of jump racing at Ascot |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/desert-orchid-thriller-the-highlight-of-50-years-of-jump-racing-at-ascot/8769 |website=Racing Post |date=24 November 2017}}</ref>

In October 1941 "A" Company of the 70th Bn. The [[Middlesex Regiment]] D.C.O moved into Hurst Park Racecourse for several months before moving to [[Cavalry Barracks, Hounslow|Hounslow Barracks]] with the rest of the Battalion.

Some of it was kept as public access to the riverside Hurst Park, with the remainder sold for the building of the present varied height residential housing in 1962. In the summer of 2018 the site of the course's pre-parade ring became temporarily visible due to the dry conditions caused by the [[2018 British Isles heat wave]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baxter |first1=David |title=Hurst parch: racecourse returns as pre-parade ring is revealed in heatwave |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/latest/hurst-parch-racecourse-returns-as-pre-parade-ring-is-revealed-in-heatwave/339736 |website=Racing Post |date=21 July 2018}}</ref>

