{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}
{{About|the sporting term|the film production concept|Set piece (film production)}}
The term '''set piece''' or '''set play''' is used in [[association football]] and [[rugby football]] to refer to a situation when the ball is returned to open play, for example following a [[Dead ball (association football)|stoppage]], particularly in a forward area of the pitch. In the case of association football the term is normally used to refer to [[Direct free kick|free kick]]s and [[corner kick|corner]]s, but sometimes [[throw-in]]s. Many goals result from such positions, whether scored directly or indirectly. Thus defending set pieces is an important skill for [[Defender (association football)|defenders]],<ref name="bbc">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/rules_and_equipment/4685580.stm |title=Set-piece marking |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> and attacking players spend much time practicing them; set pieces are one area where tactics and routines can be worked out in training in advance of matches. Some players specialize in set pieces.<ref name="fantasy">{{cite web |url=http://www.sportinglybetter.com/2012/08/fantasy-football-tips-2012-set-piece-takers/ |title=Fantasy Football Tips 2012 – Set Piece Takers |publisher=sportinglybetter.com |accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>

